Nay, an you will not, sir, I’ll take to my heels') There is some reason for accepting Schrader's emendation men πίε dem ipsus, for in the first place the interrogative particle commonly appears as -π after along vowel (eg. quin for qui-ne), and in the second ipsus is the normal form in conjunction with se, suus, and the like. The change of ipsus into ipse, and the substitution of the full for the eurtailed form of the particle, are too common in MSS. to cause us any great scruples in altering their reading in this line. Still we have elsewhere the full form of the Inter- rogative Particle in our MSS. after an emphatic monosyllable, eg. Ter. Phorm. 448 mene uz's ?, where men is impossible.
